cal components of the cohomology. Morel uses the method developed by Langlands, Ihara, and Kottwitz, which is to compare the Grothendieck-Lefschetz fixed point formula and the Arthur-Selberg trace formula. The first problem, that of applying the fixed point formula to the intersection cohomology, is geometric in nature and is the object of the first chapter, which builds on Morel's previous work. She then turns to the group-theoretical problem of comparing these results with the trace formula, when G is a unitary group over Q. Applications are then given. In particular, the Galois representation on a G(Af)-isotypical component of the cohomology is identified at almost all places, modulo a non-explicit multiplicity. Morel also gives some results on base change from unitary groups to general linear groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aHomology theory. 0aShimura varieties. 7aMATHEMATICS / Topology.2bisacsh  aAccuracy and precision.  aAdjoint.  aAlgebraic closure.  aArchimedean property.  aAutomorphism.  aBase change map.  aBase change.  aCalculation.  aClay Mathematics Institute.  aCoefficient.  aCompact element.  aCompact space.  aComparison theorem.  aConjecture.  aConnected space.  aConnectedness.  aConstant term.  aCorollary.  aDuality (mathematics).  aExistential quantification.  aExterior algebra.  aFinite field.  aFinite set.  aFundamental lemma (Langlands program).  aGalois group.  aGeneral linear group.  aHaar measure.  aHecke algebra.  aHomomorphism.  aL-function.  aLogarithm.  aMathematical induction.  aMathematician.  aMaximal compact subgroup.  aMaximal ideal.  aMorphism.  aNeighbourhood (mathematics).  aOpen set.  aParabolic induction.  aPermutation.  aPrime number.  aRamanujan–Petersson conjecture.  aReductive group